    • dev - Tables supporting compilation of programs
      • dev.arch - System architecture

      • dev.htmlentity - Known HTML entity strings & codes
      • dev.include - A site where one file includes another
      • dev.license - Source code license
      • dev.linelim -

      • dev.msgfile - File in repo containing messages that should be normalized during CI
      • dev.noindent - Indicates that a file should not be automatically indented
      • dev.opt_type - Type of option (used in tool_opt)
      • dev.package - OpenACR package

      • dev.pkgkey - Keys belonging to the OpenACR package
      • dev.readme - File containing documentation

      • dev.scriptfile - Known script file
      • dev.srcfile - Source file or header (key is pathname)

    • dmmeta - Tables holding metadata (data model meta)
      • dmmeta.anonfld - Omit field name where possible (command line, enums, constants)
      • dmmeta.argvtype - Customize parsing of command lines (rarely used)
      • dmmeta.basepool - Specify pool to be used for allocating elements of a type
      • dmmeta.bitfld - Specify offset/width of a bitfield within another field
      • dmmeta.cafter - Control amc processing order for unrelated types (used in rare situations)
      • dmmeta.cascdel - Request cascading delete of referenced rows
      • dmmeta.ccmp - Generate hash function
      • dmmeta.cdflt - Specify default value for single-value types that lack fields
      • dmmeta.cextern - Externally defined ctype (a struct from system header, or from a c++ library)
      • dmmeta.cfast - FAST properties for ctype
      • dmmeta.cfmt - Specify options for printing/reading ctypes into multiple formats
      • dmmeta.cget - Generate state functions for these ctypes
      • dmmeta.charset - Generate functions to determine if a character is a member of a set
      • dmmeta.chash - Generate hash function
      • dmmeta.cppfunc - Value of field provided by this expression
      • dmmeta.cppkeyword - Built-in C++ keyword
      • dmmeta.cpptype - Specify whether a ctype can be passed by value, and other c++ options
      • dmmeta.csize - Specify size/alignment for built-in C++ types
      • dmmeta.cstr - Specify that type behaves like a string
      • dmmeta.ctype - Struct
      • dmmeta.ctypelen - Size of Ctype
      • dmmeta.dispatch - Generate code for a multi-way branch
      • dmmeta.dispatch_msg - Add message to a dispatch
      • dmmeta.dispctx - Use context with dispatch
      • dmmeta.dispfilter - Generate filter function on dispatch
      • dmmeta.dispsig - Cryptographic signature of all dispatches
      • dmmeta.dispsigcheck - Check signature of input data against executable’s version
      • dmmeta.disptrace - Generate trace fields (cycles, counts) for all dispatch branches
      • dmmeta.falias - Alias field
      • dmmeta.fastenc -
      • dmmeta.fastinstr -
      • dmmeta.fastop -
      • dmmeta.fbase - Customize imported Base fields
      • dmmeta.fbigend - Annotate field as having big-endian storage
      • dmmeta.fbitset - Generate bitset functions over integer field or array
      • dmmeta.fbuf - Buffer for reading/writing messages, works with Iohook
      • dmmeta.fbufdir - Buffer direction (in,out)
      • dmmeta.fbuftype - Buffer type
      • dmmeta.fcast - Generate implicit conversion from field to c++ expression
      • dmmeta.fcleanup - Request user-implemented function to be called at Uninit time for a field
      • dmmeta.fcmap - Bidirectional mapping between fconst values
      • dmmeta.fcmdline - Annotate field that holds process command line
      • dmmeta.fcmp - Request versionsort or case-insensitive sort for field
      • dmmeta.fcompact - Request compaction upon removal from index
      • dmmeta.fconst - Specify enum value (integer + string constant) for a field
      • dmmeta.fcurs - Request generation of custom cursor
      • dmmeta.fdec - Specify that field has an implied # of decimal places and specify formatting options
      • dmmeta.fdelay - Control elapsed time between execution of a step
      • dmmeta.ffast - FAST properties for field
      • dmmeta.fflag - Options for command-line flags
      • dmmeta.field - Specify field of a struct
      • dmmeta.findrem - Request generation of FindRemove function
      • dmmeta.finput - Describe input table of a program
      • dmmeta.fldoffset - Assert field offset - will result in compile-time error if violated
      • dmmeta.floadtuples - Request that process automatically load any input tables on startup
      • dmmeta.fnoremove - Omit any functions for removing elements from table; Table is append-only
      • dmmeta.foutput - Generate function to save index/table back to disk
      • dmmeta.fprefix - Mapping between field prefix and Reftype
      • dmmeta.fregx - Specify options for command-line regx field
      • dmmeta.fsort - Generate custom sort function for array field
      • dmmeta.fstep - Generate a main loop step to be executed whenever a field is non-empty
      • dmmeta.ftrace - Generate cycle/step counting fields for a step
      • dmmeta.ftuple -
      • dmmeta.func -
      • dmmeta.funique - This field must be unique in the table. Not needed for primary key
      • dmmeta.fuserinit - Add user-defined initialization function for field (see fcleanup)
      • dmmeta.fwddecl - Request forward declaration of a field
      • dmmeta.gconst - Import ssim table columns as fconst for a field
      • dmmeta.gstatic - Load entries for this table at startup time
      • dmmeta.gsymbol - Create C++ symbols from entries in ssim table
      • dmmeta.hashtype - Hash function type
      • dmmeta.hook - Required on Hook fields
      • dmmeta.inlary - Generate inline array of fixed or variable length (all entries fit within parent struct)
      • dmmeta.lenfld - Specify which gives length of varlen portion in bytes
      • dmmeta.listtype - Specify structure of linked list based on field prefix
      • dmmeta.llist - Options for Llist field
      • dmmeta.logcat - Log category
      • dmmeta.main - Generate Main function for namespace
      • dmmeta.msgtype - Specify message type for each eligible message, controls dispatch
      • dmmeta.nocascdel - Remove cascade delete for this index
      • dmmeta.nossimfile - Indicates that ssimfile does not exist for this ssimdb ctype
      • dmmeta.noxref - Explicitly specify that no x-ref exists between tables (don’t use unless forced)
      • dmmeta.ns - Namespace (for in-memory database, protocol, etc)
      • dmmeta.nscpp - Generate C++ code for this namespace
      • dmmeta.nsdb - Annotate ssimdb namespaces
      • dmmeta.nsfast - Whether namespace is FAST
      • dmmeta.nsinclude - Explicitly specify a C++ include file for namespace
      • dmmeta.nsjs - Generate JavaScript code for this namespace
      • dmmeta.nsproto - Annotate protocol namespace (collection of types, no state)
      • dmmeta.nstype - Namespace type
      • dmmeta.nsversion - Namespace version
      • dmmeta.nsx - Control code-generation and exception handling options for process/library
      • dmmeta.numstr - Add functions to read numbers out of a string field
      • dmmeta.pack - Request byte-packing of structure fields
      • dmmeta.pmaskfld - Specify which field holds presence mask bits (one for each field in struct)
      • dmmeta.pmaskfld_member - Explicit field-to-pmask association
      • dmmeta.pnew - Generate custom constructor (placement new), for use with binary protocols
      • dmmeta.pnewtype - Type of fbuf
      • dmmeta.printfmt - Print format
      • dmmeta.ptrary - Required for fields with reftype:Ptrary
      • dmmeta.reftype - Field type constructor (e.g. reference type)
      • dmmeta.rowid - Initialize field to row id of element
      • dmmeta.smallstr - Generated fixed-length padded or length-delimited string field
      • dmmeta.sortfld - Specify what field an index (Bheap,Atree) is sorted on
      • dmmeta.sorttype - Sort type
      • dmmeta.sqltype - Mapping of ctype -> SQL expression
      • dmmeta.ssimfile - File with ssim tuples
      • dmmeta.ssimreq - Extended constraints for ssim records
      • dmmeta.ssimsort - Define sort order for ssimfile
      • dmmeta.ssimvolatile - Types based on ssim files marked this way cannot be cross-referenced
      • dmmeta.steptype - Type of scheduler step
      • dmmeta.strfmt - Cfmt conversion type (misnomer, not necessarily a string)
      • dmmeta.strtype - Type of small string
      • dmmeta.substr - Specify that the field value is computed from a substring of another field
      • dmmeta.svtype - Table for determining ctype from separated value file
      • dmmeta.tary - Indirect linear dynamically alocated array (used for strings, arrays of data, etc)
      • dmmeta.thash - Hash index, required for fields with reftype Thash
      • dmmeta.tracefld - Trace fields
      • dmmeta.tracerec - Trace record
      • dmmeta.typefld - Specifies which field of a message carries the type
      • dmmeta.usertracefld - Add custom user trace fields to process’s trace struct
      • dmmeta.xref - Specify how to cross-reference (i.e. project, or group-by) one record with another

  982// --- atf_amc.Bytebuf
  983// create: atf_amc.FDb.bytebuf (Cppstack)
  984struct Bytebuf { // atf_amc.Bytebuf
  985    u8              in_elems[64];      // pointer to elements of inline array
  986    i32             in_start;          // beginning of valid bytes (in bytes)
  987    i32             in_end;            // end of valid bytes (in bytes)
  988    bool            in_eof;            // no more data will be written to buffer
  989    algo::Errcode   in_err;            // system error code
  990    bool            in_epoll_enable;   // use epoll?
  991    enum { in_max = 64 };
  992    Bytebuf();
  993private:
  994    // reftype Fbuf of atf_amc.Bytebuf.in prohibits copy
  995    Bytebuf(const Bytebuf&){ /*disallow copy constructor */}
  996    void operator =(const Bytebuf&){ /*disallow direct assignment */}
  997};
  998
  999// Detect incoming message in buffer and return it
 1000// Look for valid message at current position in the buffer.
 1001// If message is already there, return a pointer to it. Do not skip message (call SkipMsg to do that).
 1002// If there is no message, read once from underlying file descriptor and try again.
 1003// The message is any number of bytes > 0
 1004//
 1005// func:atf_amc.Bytebuf.in.GetMsg
 1006algo::aryptr<char>   in_GetMsg(atf_amc::Bytebuf& bytebuf) __attribute__((nothrow));
 1007// Return max. number of bytes in the buffer.
 1008// func:atf_amc.Bytebuf.in.Max
 1009i32                  in_Max(atf_amc::Bytebuf& bytebuf) __attribute__((nothrow));
 1010// Return number of bytes in the buffer.
 1011// func:atf_amc.Bytebuf.in.N
 1012i32                  in_N(atf_amc::Bytebuf& bytebuf) __attribute__((__warn_unused_result__, nothrow, pure));
 1013// Empty bfufer
 1014// Discard contents of the buffer.
 1015// func:atf_amc.Bytebuf.in.RemoveAll
 1016void                 in_RemoveAll(atf_amc::Bytebuf& bytebuf) __attribute__((nothrow));
 1017// Skip N bytes when reading
 1018// Mark some buffer contents as read.
 1019//
 1020// func:atf_amc.Bytebuf.in.SkipBytes
 1021void                 in_SkipBytes(atf_amc::Bytebuf& bytebuf, int n) __attribute__((nothrow));
 1022// Attempt to write buffer contents to fd
 1023// Write bytes to the buffer. If the entire block is written, return true,
 1024// Otherwise return false.
 1025// Bytes in the buffer are potentially shifted left to make room for the message.
 1026//
 1027// func:atf_amc.Bytebuf.in.WriteAll
 1028bool                 in_WriteAll(atf_amc::Bytebuf& bytebuf, u8 *in, i32 in_n) __attribute__((nothrow));
 1029
 1030// Set all fields to initial values.
 1031// func:atf_amc.Bytebuf..Init
 1032void                 Bytebuf_Init(atf_amc::Bytebuf& bytebuf);
 1033// print string representation of ROW to string STR
 1034// cfmt:atf_amc.Bytebuf.String  printfmt:Raw
 1035// func:atf_amc.Bytebuf..Print
 1036void                 Bytebuf_Print(atf_amc::Bytebuf& row, algo::cstring& str) __attribute__((nothrow));

 1038// --- atf_amc.BytebufDyn
 1039// create: atf_amc.FDb.bytebuf_dyn (Cppstack)
 1040struct BytebufDyn { // atf_amc.BytebufDyn
 1041    u8*             in_elems;          //   NULL  pointer to elements of indirect array
 1042    u32             in_max;            //   0  current length of allocated array
 1043    i32             in_start;          // beginning of valid bytes (in bytes)
 1044    i32             in_end;            // end of valid bytes (in bytes)
 1045    bool            in_eof;            // no more data will be written to buffer
 1046    algo::Errcode   in_err;            // system error code
 1047    bool            in_epoll_enable;   // use epoll?

 1049    ~BytebufDyn();

 1053    void operator =(const BytebufDyn&){ /*disallow direct assignment */}
 1054};

 1064// Set buffer size.
 1065// Unconditionally reallocate buffer to have size NEW_MAX
 1066// If the buffer has data in it, NEW_MAX is adjusted so that the data is not lost
 1067// (best to call this before filling the buffer)
 1068// func:atf_amc.BytebufDyn.in.Realloc
 1069void                 in_Realloc(atf_amc::BytebufDyn& bytebuf_dyn, int new_max) __attribute__((nothrow));
 1070// Return max. number of bytes in the buffer.

 1076// Empty bfufer
 1077// Discard contents of the buffer.
 1078// func:atf_amc.BytebufDyn.in.RemoveAll

 1697// --- atf_amc.FCascdel
 1698// create: atf_amc.FDb.cascdel (Tpool)
 1699// access: atf_amc.FCascdel.p_parent (Upptr)
 1700// access: atf_amc.FCascdel.child_ptr (Ptr)
 1701// access: atf_amc.FCascdel.c_child_ptrary (Ptrary)
 1702// access: atf_amc.FCascdel.ind_child_thash (Thash)
 1703// access: atf_amc.FCascdel.bh_child_bheap (Bheap)
 1704// access: atf_amc.FCascdel.zd_childlist (Llist)
 1705// access: atf_amc.FCascdel.tr_child_atree (Atree)
 1706struct FCascdel { // atf_amc.FCascdel: Test type for cascade delete
 1707    atf_amc::FCascdel*    p_parent;                        // reference to parent row
 1708    u32                   key;                             //   0
 1709    u32                   type;                            //   0
 1710    atf_amc::FCascdel*    child_ptr;                       // optional pointer

 1712    u32                   c_child_ptrary_n;                // array of pointers
 1713    u32                   c_child_ptrary_max;              // capacity of allocated array
 1714    atf_amc::FCascdel**   ind_child_thash_buckets_elems;   // pointer to bucket array
 1715    i32                   ind_child_thash_buckets_n;       // number of elements in bucket array
 1716    i32                   ind_child_thash_n;               // number of elements in the hash table
 1717    atf_amc::FCascdel*    ind_child_thash_next;            // hash next
 1718    atf_amc::FCascdel**   bh_child_bheap_elems;            // binary heap by key
 1719    i32                   bh_child_bheap_n;                // number of elements in the heap
 1720    i32                   bh_child_bheap_max;              // max elements in bh_child_bheap_elems
 1721    i32                   bh_child_bheap_idx;              // index in heap; -1 means not-in-heap
 1722    atf_amc::FCascdel*    zd_childlist_head;               // zero-terminated doubly linked list
 1723    i32                   zd_childlist_n;                  // zero-terminated doubly linked list
 1724    atf_amc::FCascdel*    zd_childlist_tail;               // pointer to last element
 1725    atf_amc::FCascdel*    zd_childlist_next;               // zslist link; -1 means not-in-list
 1726    atf_amc::FCascdel*    zd_childlist_prev;               // previous element
 1727    atf_amc::FCascdel*    tr_child_atree_root;             // Root of the tree
 1728    i32                   tr_child_atree_n;                // number of elements in the tree
 1729    atf_amc::FCascdel*    tr_child_atree_up;               // pointer to parent
 1730    atf_amc::FCascdel*    tr_child_atree_left;             // Left child
 1731    atf_amc::FCascdel*    tr_child_atree_right;            // Right child
 1732    i32                   tr_child_atree_depth;            // Depth
 1733    bool                  cascdel_c_child_ptrary_in_ary;   //   false  membership flag
 1734    atf_amc::FCascdel*    cascdel_next;                    // Pointer to next free element int tpool
 1735private:
 1736    friend atf_amc::FCascdel&   cascdel_Alloc() __attribute__((__warn_unused_result__, nothrow));
 1737    friend atf_amc::FCascdel*   cascdel_AllocMaybe() __attribute__((__warn_unused_result__, nothrow));

 5418// --- atf_amc.Linebuf
 5419// create: atf_amc.FDb.linebuf (Cppstack)
 5420struct Linebuf { // atf_amc.Linebuf
 5421    u8              in_elems[64];      // pointer to elements of inline array
 5422    i32             in_start;          // beginning of valid bytes (in bytes)
 5423    i32             in_end;            // end of valid bytes (in bytes)
 5424    bool            in_eof;            // no more data will be written to buffer
 5425    algo::Errcode   in_err;            // system error code
 5426    bool            in_msgvalid;       // current message is valid
 5427    i32             in_msglen;         // current message length
 5428    bool            in_epoll_enable;   // use epoll?
 5429    enum { in_max = 64 };
 5430    Linebuf();
 5431private:
 5432    // reftype Fbuf of atf_amc.Linebuf.in prohibits copy
 5433    Linebuf(const Linebuf&){ /*disallow copy constructor */}
 5434    void operator =(const Linebuf&){ /*disallow direct assignment */}
 5435};
 5436
 5437// Detect incoming message in buffer and return it
 5438// Look for valid message at current position in the buffer.
 5439// If message is already there, return a pointer to it. Do not skip message (call SkipMsg to do that).
 5440// If there is no message, read once from underlying file descriptor and try again.
 5441// The message is found by looking for delimiter '\n'.
 5442// The return value is an aryptr. If ret.elems is non-NULL, the message is valid (possibly empty).
 5443// If ret.elems is NULL, no message can be extracted from buffer.
 5444// The returned aryptr excludes the trailing deliminter.
 5445// SkipMsg will skip both the line and the deliminter.
 5446// A partial line at the end of input is NOT returned (TODO?)
 5447//
 5448// func:atf_amc.Linebuf.in.GetMsg
 5449algo::aryptr<char>   in_GetMsg(atf_amc::Linebuf& linebuf) __attribute__((nothrow));
 5450// Return max. number of bytes in the buffer.
 5451// func:atf_amc.Linebuf.in.Max
 5452i32                  in_Max(atf_amc::Linebuf& linebuf) __attribute__((nothrow));
 5453// Return number of bytes in the buffer.
 5454// func:atf_amc.Linebuf.in.N
 5455i32                  in_N(atf_amc::Linebuf& linebuf) __attribute__((__warn_unused_result__, nothrow, pure));
 5456// Empty bfufer
 5457// Discard contents of the buffer.
 5458// func:atf_amc.Linebuf.in.RemoveAll
 5459void                 in_RemoveAll(atf_amc::Linebuf& linebuf) __attribute__((nothrow));
 5460// Skip N bytes when reading
 5461// Mark some buffer contents as read.
 5462//
 5463// func:atf_amc.Linebuf.in.SkipBytes
 5464void                 in_SkipBytes(atf_amc::Linebuf& linebuf, int n) __attribute__((nothrow));
 5465// Skip current message, if any
 5466// Skip current message, if any.
 5467// func:atf_amc.Linebuf.in.SkipMsg
 5468void                 in_SkipMsg(atf_amc::Linebuf& linebuf) __attribute__((nothrow));
 5469// Attempt to write buffer contents to fd
 5470// Write bytes to the buffer. If the entire block is written, return true,
 5471// Otherwise return false.
 5472// Bytes in the buffer are potentially shifted left to make room for the message.
 5473//
 5474// func:atf_amc.Linebuf.in.WriteAll
 5475bool                 in_WriteAll(atf_amc::Linebuf& linebuf, u8 *in, i32 in_n) __attribute__((nothrow));
 5476
 5477// Set all fields to initial values.
 5478// func:atf_amc.Linebuf..Init

 5899
 5900// Return pointer to optional last element (NULL if none)
 5901// The parent's length field is assumed to have already been checked for validity.
 5902// If the parent's lengthis too short to allow a full-sized o, return NULL.
 5903// Since the last element is itself variable-length, two more checks are applied:
 5904// If o's length field value is too short, return NULL.
 5905// If o's length field value extends past parent's allowed length, return NULL.
 5906// func:atf_amc.MsgLTO.o.Get
 5907atf_amc::MsgHdrLT*   o_Get(atf_amc::MsgLTO& parent) __attribute__((__warn_unused_result__, nothrow));

 5912void                 o_Print(atf_amc::MsgLTO& parent, cstring &out) __attribute__((nothrow));
 5913// Convert string to field. Return success value
 5914// func:atf_amc.MsgLTO.o.ReadStrptrMaybe
 5915bool                 o_ReadStrptrMaybe(atf_amc::MsgLTO &parent, algo::strptr in_str) __attribute__((nothrow));
 5916// Insert row into all appropriate indices. If error occurs, store error
 5917// in algo_lib::_db.errtext and return false. Caller must Delete or Unref such row.
 5918// func:atf_amc.MsgLTO.o.XrefMaybe
 5919bool                 o_XrefMaybe(atf_amc::MsgHdrLT &row);
 5920
 5921// func:atf_amc.MsgLTO..ReadFieldMaybe

 5923// Any varlen fields are returned in algo_lib::_db.varlenbuf if set
 5924// Read fields of atf_amc::MsgLTO from an ascii string.
 5925// The format of the string is an ssim Tuple
 5926// func:atf_amc.MsgLTO..ReadStrptrMaybe
 5927bool                 MsgLTO_ReadStrptrMaybe(atf_amc::MsgLTO &parent, algo::strptr in_str) __attribute__((nothrow));
 5928// Message length (uses length field)
 5929// func:atf_amc.MsgLTO..GetMsgLength
 5930i32                  GetMsgLength(const atf_amc::MsgLTO& parent) __attribute__((nothrow));

 6008// --- atf_amc.Msgbuf
 6009// create: atf_amc.FDb.msgbuf (Cppstack)
 6010// global access: cd_in_msg (Llist)
 6011struct Msgbuf { // atf_amc.Msgbuf
 6012    atf_amc::Msgbuf*    cd_in_msg_next;           // zslist link; -1 means not-in-list
 6013    atf_amc::Msgbuf*    cd_in_msg_prev;           // previous element
 6014    u8                  in_elems[64];             // pointer to elements of inline array
 6015    i32                 in_start;                 // beginning of valid bytes (in bytes)
 6016    i32                 in_end;                   // end of valid bytes (in bytes)
 6017    bool                in_eof;                   // no more data will be written to buffer
 6018    algo::Errcode       in_err;                   // system error code
 6019    bool                in_msgvalid;              // current message is valid
 6020    i32                 in_msglen;                // current message length
 6021    algo_lib::FIohook   in_iohook;                // edge-triggered hook for refilling buffer
 6022    bool                in_epoll_enable;          // use epoll?
 6023    enum { in_max = 64 };
 6024    u8                  out_extra_elems[64];      // pointer to elements of inline array
 6025    i32                 out_extra_start;          // beginning of valid bytes (in bytes)
 6026    i32                 out_extra_end;            // end of valid bytes (in bytes)
 6027    bool                out_extra_eof;            // no more data will be written to buffer
 6028    algo::Errcode       out_extra_err;            // system error code
 6029    bool                out_extra_epoll_enable;   // use epoll?
 6030    enum { out_extra_max = 64 };
 6031    u8                  in_extra_elems[64];       // pointer to elements of inline array
 6032    i32                 in_extra_start;           // beginning of valid bytes (in bytes)
 6033    i32                 in_extra_end;             // end of valid bytes (in bytes)
 6034    bool                in_extra_eof;             // no more data will be written to buffer
 6035    algo::Errcode       in_extra_err;             // system error code
 6036    bool                in_extra_msgvalid;        // current message is valid
 6037    i32                 in_extra_msglen;          // current message length
 6038    bool                in_extra_epoll_enable;    // use epoll?
 6039    enum { in_extra_max = 64 };
 6040    Msgbuf();
 6041    ~Msgbuf();
 6042private:
 6043    Msgbuf(const Msgbuf&){ /*disallow copy constructor */}
 6044    void operator =(const Msgbuf&){ /*disallow direct assignment */}
 6045};
